{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521143"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:32:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:32:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13566"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13566"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.3,0.42,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49932"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6184"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35191"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"6417"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13272"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13687"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13816"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42892"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44655"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49932"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old construction worker is brought to the emergency department after a scaffolding collapse at a construction site. He was struck by falling debris and pinned against a wall, resulting in significant trauma to his pelvic region. On arrival, he complains of excruciating pelvic pain, inability to pass urine, and swelling around the perineum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 110/min, temperature 37.2\u00b0C, respiratory rate 22/min and SpO\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E\u00a092% on room air. Physical examination finds ecchymosis, blood at the urethral meatus, and tenderness over the pubic symphysis. A FAST scan shows a distended urinary bladder and no free fluid in the peritoneal cavity. A pelvic X-ray confirms pubic rami fractures on both sides of the symphysis pubis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Computed tomography (CT) urography","Indwelling urinary catheter (IDC) insertion","Retrograde urethrography","Renal Ultrasound","Voiding cystourethrogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the clinical presentation of acute urinary retention, blood at the urethral meatus and suspected pelvic trauma, it is quite likely that this patient has sustained a urethral injury. \u003Cstrong\u003ERetrograde urethrography\u003C/strong\u003E is the modality of choice to investigate urethral injuries. Retrograde urethrography\u00a0involves injecting contrast into the urethra to visualise any urethral disruptions. Extravasation of the contrast without opacification of the urinary bladder would indicate complete avulsion of the membranous urethra. In partial urethral avulsion, there will be contrast extravasation with some degree of bladder opacification, whereas a good urethral and bladder opacification without leakage of contrast rules out urethral trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography (CT) urography\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is incorrect in this scenario because it primarily evaluates the urinary system within the abdomen, including the kidneys, ureters, and bladder. While CT urography can detect injuries to these structures, it may not adequately assess the urethra, especially the penile urethra, which is crucial in cases of suspected urethral trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndwelling urinary catheter (IDC) insertion \u003C/strong\u003Ethrough the urethra into the bladder to drain urine is a common procedure for managing urinary retention. However, in the context of suspected urethral trauma, attempting to insert an IDC insertion without prior imaging can cause or exacerbate existing damage to the urethra. Therefore, it is crucial to confirm the integrity of the urethra before catheter insertion to avoid further complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal ultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Eis a non-invasive imaging technique to view the kidneys and bladder. It is commonly used to evaluate kidney size, structure, and position, detect kidney stones, cysts, and tumours, and assess urinary tract obstructions. While it is safe and does not involve radiation exposure, renal ultrasound has limited utility in acute trauma settings for evaluating urethral injuries. Its primary role is assessing renal pathology and bladder conditions rather than detailed urethral evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVoiding cystourethrogram\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0(VCUG) involves filling the bladder with water-soluble contrast and observing urine flow through the urethra during voiding. VCUG primarily evaluates bladder and urethral function during voiding and is commonly used to diagnose conditions such as vesicoureteral reflux or lower urinary tract dysfunction. VCUG may not be the most appropriate initial investigation in the acute setting of suspected urethral trauma, especially if there are concerns about urinary retention and the need for immediate intervention. Any attempt to blindly fill the bladder with contrast (via the urethra) could worsen any existing injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diagnosis of urethral trauma secondary to pelvic fracture involves prompt assessment with retrograde urethrography to determine the extent of the injury."],"references":["Barratt RC, Bernard J, Mundy AR, Greenwell TJ. Pelvic fracture urethral injury in males-mechanisms of injury, management options and outcomes. Transl Androl Urol. 2018 Mar;7(Suppl 1):S29-S62. doi: 10.21037/tau.2017.12.35. PMID: 29644168; PMCID: PMC5881191.","Patel AB, Osterberg EC, Satarasinghe PN, Wenzel JL, Akbani ST, Sahi SL, Emigh BJ, Wolf JS Jr, Brown CVR. Urethral Injuries: Diagnostic and Management Strategies for Critical Care and Trauma Clinicians. J Clin Med. 2023 Feb 13;12(4):1495. doi: 10.3390/jcm12041495. PMID: 36836030; PMCID: PMC9959137.","Knipe H. Urethral injury | Radiology Reference Article | Radiopaedia.org [Internet]. Radiopaedia. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/urethral-injury-1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35191"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13566"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35191"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-04T19:17:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-04T19:18:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6184"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49932"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"m